<section xml:id="sec-tree-diagrams" original="STAT/modules/m79617/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
  <title>Tree Diagrams</title>

  <!-- Content summary: Calculating probability using tree diagram -->

  <objectives>
 Calculate probabilities using tree diagrams
  </objectives>

  <!-- Add <insight> here -->

  <!-- BEGIN BORROWED CONTENT -->

<!-- Borrowed from STAT fs-idp113760352: Tree Diagrams -->
  
  <p>A <term>tree diagram</term> is a special type of graph used to determine the outcomes of an experiment. It consists of <em>branches</em> that are labeled with either frequencies or probabilities. Tree diagrams can make some probability problems easier to visualize and solve. The following example illustrates how to use a tree diagram:</p>
  
  <example xml:id="STAT-jKrytuApIf" original="STAT/modules/m79617/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <statement>
        <p>a. List the 24 <em>BR</em> outcomes: <m>B</m>1<m>R</m>1, <m>B</m>1<m>R</m>2, <m>B</m>1<m>R</m>3, . . .</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>a. We know that there will be 24 different possible outcomes because there are eight ways to draw blue and three ways to draw red. Make a systematic list of possible outcomes that consist of a blue marble on the first draw and a red marble on the second draw.</p>
        <p>
          <m>B</m>1<m>R</m>1, <m>B</m>1<m>R</m>2, <m>B</m>1<m>R</m>3 <m>B</m>2<m>R</m>1, <m>B</m>2<m>R</m>2, <m>B</m>2<m>R</m>3 <m>B</m>3<m>R</m>1, <m>B</m>3<m>R</m>2, <m>B</m>3<m>R</m>3 <m>B</m>4<m>R</m>1, <m>B</m>4<m>R</m>2, <m>B</m>4<m>R</m>3 <m>B</m>5<m>R</m>1, <m>B</m>5<m>R</m>2, <m>B</m>5<m>R</m>3 <m>B</m>6<m>R</m>1, <m>B</m>6<m>R</m>2, <m>B</m>6<m>R</m>3 <m>B</m>7<m>R</m>1, <m>B</m>7<m>R</m>2, <m>B</m>7<m>R</m>3 <m>B</m>8<m>R</m>1, <m>B</m>8<m>R</m>2, <m>B</m>8<m>R</m>3</p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  
  <example xml:id="STAT-6X739tbRpY" original="STAT/modules/m79617/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <statement>
        <p>a. <em>P</em>(<em>RR</em>) = ________</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>a. <em>P</em>(<em>RR</em>) = <m>(\frac{3}{11})(\frac{2}{10})=\frac{6}{110}</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  
  <example xml:id="STAT-mZxQaow6b4" original="STAT/modules/m79617/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <statement>
        <ol>
          <li>Which shows the probability that both kittens are tabby? <m>\text{ a. }(\frac{1}{2})(\frac{1}{2})</m>
            <m>\text{ b. }(\frac{4}{9})(\frac{4}{9})</m>
            <m>\text{ c. }(\frac{4}{9})(\frac{3}{8})</m>
            <m>\text{ d. }(\frac{4}{9})(\frac{5}{9})</m>
          </li>
          <li>What is the probability that one kitten of each coloring is selected? <m>\text{ a. }(\frac{4}{9})(\frac{5}{9})</m>
            <m>\text{ b. }(\frac{4}{9})(\frac{5}{8})</m>
            <m>\text{ c. }(\frac{4}{9})(\frac{5}{9})+(\frac{5}{9})(\frac{4}{9})</m>
            <m>\text{ d. }(\frac{4}{9})(\frac{5}{8})+(\frac{5}{9})(\frac{4}{8})</m>
          </li>
          <li>What is the probability that a tabby is chosen as the second kitten when a black kitten was chosen as the first?</li>
          <li>What is the probability of choosing two kittens of the same color?</li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>a. <m>(\frac{4}{9})(\frac{3}{8})</m>, b. <m>(\frac{4}{9})(\frac{5}{8})+(\frac{5}{9})(\frac{4}{8})</m>, c. <m>\frac{4}{8}</m>, d. <m>\frac{32}{72}</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  
  <convention>
      <p>This section <xref ref="sec-tree-diagrams" text="title"/> is adapted from "<url href="https://github.com/openstax/osbooks-statistics/tree/ee0efc177a01145d28d9429fc309e331fab9c566/modules/m79617/index.cnxml">Tree Diagrams</url>" in Open STAX Statistics, used under <url href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/deed.en">CC-BY-4.0</url>.</p>
    </convention>

  <!-- END BORROWED CONTENT -->
</section>
